"""
MKT Christ in Every Verse — Micah chapters 1–6 (84 missing verses; 5:2 already exists)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-micah-1-6.py

Key decisions:
- Mic 4:1-3 treated as shadow of the eschatological new creation gathering (Isa 2 parallel)
- Mic 2:12-13 (the Breaker/Shepherd) treated as type: the one who breaks through = Christ
- Mic 4:8 (Migdal-eder, tower of the flock) treated as type: Jewish tradition links Bethlehem's
  watchtower to the Messiah; proximity to Micah 5:2 supports the connection
- Mic 5:1 (strike the ruler on the cheek) treated as shadow of Matt 27:30
- Mic 6:8 treated as shadow pointing to Matt 23:23: the ethical core the NT identifies as the
  weightier matters of the law
- Mic 6:3 (What have I done to you?) treated as revelation pointing to John 15:13 / Rom 5:8
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MICAH = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>A theme: the prophetic superscription — &ldquo;the word of the LORD that came to Micah&rdquo; — situates Micah in the long tradition of prophets through whom YHWH spoke before speaking through his Son (Heb 1:1-2). Micah of Moresheth is a rural outsider; his commission without institutional credentials continues the pattern of Amos and anticipates the fishermen-apostles. His ministry spans three kings (Jotham, Ahaz, Hezekiah), covering both the fall of Samaria (722 BCE) and Hezekiah's reformation — the full arc from judgment to conditional rescue.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Hear, all you peoples... for the Lord GOD will be a witness against you.&rdquo; The universal summons of all the earth to hear YHWH's testimony reveals the God of universal sovereignty — Israel's covenant Lord is also the judge of all nations. The NT develops this into the Great Assize: &ldquo;God has fixed a day on which he will judge the world in righteousness by a man whom he has appointed&rdquo; (Acts 17:31). The witness who testifies against humanity is the same Lord who, in Christ, provides the one way of escape from the verdict.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;For behold, the LORD is coming out of his place; he will come down and tread upon the high places of the earth.&rdquo; The divine theophany — YHWH descending from his heavenly dwelling to earth — is the OT form of the incarnation. The theological pattern is clear: YHWH leaves his place and comes down. In the incarnation this descent becomes total and irreversible: &ldquo;the Word became flesh and dwelt among us&rdquo; (John 1:14). The judgment-theophany that Micah describes becomes in Christ a rescue-theophany — the same descent, with a different purpose and a permanent dwelling.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A shadow: the cosmic convulsion at YHWH's coming — mountains melting, valleys splitting — is the OT theophany language for the weight of the divine presence touching the created order. The NT uses the same imagery for the final coming of Christ: &ldquo;every mountain and island was removed from its place&rdquo; (Rev 6:14); &ldquo;the earth and the sky fled away&rdquo; (Rev 20:11). The wax-before-fire image (total dissolution before the divine presence) reveals the absolute ontological asymmetry between the Creator and creation — a truth the incarnation does not diminish but demonstrates: the one before whom mountains melt chose to become an infant in Bethlehem.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A revelation of God: the identification of transgression and sin as the cause of the coming judgment — &ldquo;all this is for the transgression of Jacob and for the sins of the house of Israel&rdquo; — reveals the moral coherence of divine judgment. Sin has consequences; YHWH's judgment is not arbitrary but morally structured. The NT's diagnosis of the human condition (Rom 3:23: &ldquo;all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God&rdquo;) is the universal form of Micah's specific indictment. The good news is that the one who came down to judge (v3) is also the one who bore the judgment: &ldquo;God made him who knew no sin to be sin for us&rdquo; (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: the coming destruction of Samaria — &ldquo;I will make Samaria a heap in the open country&rdquo; — executes the covenant curses for persistent idolatry. The northern kingdom falls first because its idolatrous worship (the golden calves at Bethel and Dan) was most flagrant. This is the shadow of the NT pattern: judgment begins with the house of God (1 Pet 4:17); the one who received the greater light bears the greater accountability. Christ weeps over Jerusalem as Micah mourns over Samaria (Luke 19:41-44) — the judgment of the beloved city is the deepest grief of the faithful prophet and the faithful Son.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A shadow: the wound is described as incurable — the judgment of Samaria will come to the very gate of Jerusalem. The incurability of the human condition apart from divine intervention is a recurrent OT diagnosis (Jer 17:9: &ldquo;the heart is deceitful above all things and beyond cure — who can understand it?&rdquo;). Only the one who is the physician (Luke 5:31-32) can heal what is beyond human cure; only the one who bore the wound (Isa 53:5: &ldquo;by his wounds we are healed&rdquo;) can address the incurable wound of covenant transgression.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A theme: Micah's personal mourning — &ldquo;for this I will lament and wail; I will go stripped and naked... for her wounds are incurable&rdquo; — models the prophetic grief that matches divine grief over judgment. The prophet does not observe disaster from a safe distance but enters it bodily. Christ does this completely: he does not observe human sin from a distance but enters the full consequence of it (John 11:33-35: Jesus &ldquo;was deeply moved in spirit&rdquo; and &ldquo;wept&rdquo; before the tomb of Lazarus). The mourning prophet is a type of the &ldquo;man of sorrows, acquainted with grief&rdquo; (Isa 53:3).</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: the wound reaches to Judah's gate — &ldquo;it has come to the gate of my people, to Jerusalem.&rdquo; The judgment that began in Samaria spreads; no part of the covenant people is immune. The NT develops this as the universal reach of sin: &ldquo;There is no one righteous, not even one&rdquo; (Rom 3:10, citing Ps 14:3). The wound that reaches Jerusalem's gate reaches its final destination at the cross, where the Son of David is executed outside the very gate of Jerusalem (Heb 13:12: &ldquo;Jesus also suffered outside the city gate to make the people holy through his own blood&rdquo;).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A theme: the lament over the Judean cities (v10-15) uses wordplays on town names to express the judgment — &ldquo;Tell it not in Gath&rdquo; (echoing David's lament in 2 Sam 1:20). The prohibition of mourning before enemies who would rejoice at Israel's fall reflects the honor-shame dynamic of the ANE: grief before hostile witnesses is humiliation. Christ's passion involves precisely this public humiliation before those who rejoice in it (Luke 23:35: the rulers &ldquo;sneered at him&rdquo;). The shame Micah fears for his people, Christ endured voluntarily.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A theme: the city of Shaphir (&ldquo;shame-nakedness&rdquo;) will go out naked in shame — the language of exposed guilt and covenant curse (cf. Rev 3:17-18: Laodicea told it is &ldquo;naked&rdquo; and must buy white garments from Christ). The nakedness of judgment is the condition from which Christ covers the believer: &ldquo;clothe yourselves with the Lord Jesus Christ&rdquo; (Rom 13:14); the white garments of the redeemed (Rev 7:13-14: &ldquo;washed in the blood of the Lamb&rdquo;) are the answer to the naked shame of judgment.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A theme: Zaanan (from <em>yatza</em>, to go out) — &ldquo;the inhabitants of Zaanan do not go out.&rdquo; The paralysis of fear before judgment: those who should go out are frozen by dread. The NT's contrast is the freedom that comes in Christ: &ldquo;for freedom Christ has set us free&rdquo; (Gal 5:1); &ldquo;perfect love drives out fear&rdquo; (1 John 4:18). The one who breaks through every barrier (2:13: &ldquo;the breaker goes up before them&rdquo;) frees those who are frozen in fear to go out in mission.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;hitch the steeds to the chariot, O inhabitant of Lachish — she was the beginning of sin to the daughter of Zion.&rdquo; Lachish (a fortress city) is the beginning of sin's spread southward into Judah — perhaps because of its Canaanite past or its role as the entry point for northern corruptions. The identification of the &ldquo;beginning of sin&rdquo; within the people points toward the NT's radical diagnosis: sin is not merely external influence but internal origin (Mark 7:21-23: &ldquo;from within, out of the heart of man, come evil thoughts...&rdquo;).</p>",
    "14": "<p>A theme: Moresheth-Gath (Micah's home village) will receive farewell gifts — it will be given over as a parting gift. The place where the prophet was born is not exempt from the judgment he announces; the prophet's own community falls under the word he preaches. This is the shape of authentic prophetic ministry: the messenger does not stand above the judgment but within it. Christ does this definitively — he is born in Bethlehem, the city of Judah's heritage, and is rejected by his own (John 1:11: &ldquo;he came to his own, and his own people did not receive him&rdquo;).</p>",
    "15": "<p>A shadow: YHWH will bring a conqueror against Mareshah — &ldquo;the glory of Israel shall come to Adullam.&rdquo; Adullam was the cave where David fled from Saul (1 Sam 22:1); the glory of Israel retreating to Adullam evokes David's exile. The pattern of exile and return — glory hidden, then restored — runs throughout the OT and reaches its culmination in Christ: the one who is the glory of Israel (Luke 2:32: &ldquo;a glory for your people Israel&rdquo;) is crucified outside the city in apparent defeat, then raised and glorified (John 17:5: &ldquo;glorify me in your own presence with the glory I had with you before the world existed&rdquo;).</p>",
    "16": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Make yourselves bald and cut off your hair for your pampered children; make yourselves as bald as the eagle, for they shall go from you into exile.&rdquo; The shaving of the head was the deepest sign of mourning and humiliation (Job 1:20). Children taken into exile is the worst covenant curse — the loss of the next generation. The NT's reversal: through Christ's death, those who were &ldquo;far off&rdquo; are &ldquo;brought near by the blood of Christ&rdquo; (Eph 2:13); the children scattered in exile are gathered as heirs of the new covenant family (John 11:52: &ldquo;to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&rdquo;).</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Woe to those who devise wickedness and work evil on their beds! When the morning dawns, they carry it out, because it is in their power.&rdquo; The God who reveals this woe is the God who sees what is devised on beds in the night — the omniscient judge who cannot be evaded. Christ's omniscience is expressed similarly: he &ldquo;knew what was in a man&rdquo; (John 2:25) and reads the intentions of the heart without being told (Mark 2:8). The woe against those who &ldquo;plan iniquity&rdquo; is the OT form of the NT's &ldquo;you have heard it was said... but I say to you that everyone who looks at a woman with lustful intent has already committed adultery&rdquo; (Matt 5:28) — judgment reaches the heart, not just the act.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A revelation of God: the seizure of fields and houses — &ldquo;they covet fields and seize them; they oppress a man and his house, a man and his inheritance&rdquo; — violates the Torah's land-inheritance laws (Lev 25; Num 36:7-9) which protected each family's permanent claim to the land YHWH gave them. The Naboth incident (1 Kgs 21) is the paradigmatic case. The God who condemns the seizure of the poor man's inheritance is the God whose Son declares &ldquo;Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth&rdquo; (Matt 5:5) — the land-inheritance promise is transformed into the new creation inheritance that cannot be seized.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Therefore, thus says the LORD: I am devising disaster against this family.&rdquo; YHWH's counter-planning against those who plan evil (v1: &ldquo;devise iniquity&rdquo;) — a divine measure-for-measure response. This reveals a God who acts in history with moral precision, not passively. The NT's form: &ldquo;Do not be deceived: God is not mocked, for whatever one sows, that will he also reap&rdquo; (Gal 6:7). But the cross introduces an asymmetry into the moral calculus: Christ takes the disaster that was devised against us (Isa 53:10: &ldquo;it was the will of the LORD to crush him&rdquo;) so that those who repent escape the disaster they have devised.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;We are utterly ruined; he changes the portion of my people.&rdquo; The lament that will be sung over the oppressors who become the oppressed — the reversal that judgment brings. The Magnificat enacts this same reversal at the coming of Christ: &ldquo;he has brought down the mighty from their thrones and exalted those of humble estate&rdquo; (Luke 1:52). The bitter taunt-song over those who seized others' inheritances is the OT form of Christ's &ldquo;Woe to you who are rich&rdquo; (Luke 6:24) — the reversal of fortune in the coming kingdom is structurally identical.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Therefore you will have no one to cast the line by lot in the assembly of the LORD.&rdquo; Loss of the right to allot land in the community — permanent exclusion from the covenant inheritance. The NT's warning has the same structure: &ldquo;Whoever has, more will be given; but whoever does not have, even what he has will be taken from him&rdquo; (Mark 4:25). Those who seize what is not theirs lose what they have; those who receive in faith inherit everything. Christ is the one in whom all the inheritance-promises are &ldquo;Yes and Amen&rdquo; (2 Cor 1:20).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A theme: the command to silence the prophets — &ldquo;Do not preach; one should not preach of such things&rdquo; — is the persistent attempt to suppress divine judgment before it reaches its audience. The same silencing is attempted against Christ (Mark 10:48: the crowd telling Bartimaeus to be quiet) and the apostles (Acts 4:17-18: &ldquo;commanded them not to speak... in the name of Jesus&rdquo;). The word of God cannot be ultimately silenced: &ldquo;Is not my word like fire, declares the LORD?&rdquo; (Jer 23:29). What was said of Christ is said of all faithful witnesses who proclaim judgment.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Should this be said, O house of Jacob? Is the Spirit of the LORD impatient? Are these his deeds?&rdquo; — the people question whether YHWH could really act this harshly. YHWH's response: &ldquo;Do not my words do good to him who walks uprightly?&rdquo; The Spirit of the LORD is not impatient but consistent: the word that judges the oppressor does good to the upright. Christ makes the same point about the Spirit's work: the Spirit &ldquo;will convict the world concerning sin and righteousness and judgment&rdquo; (John 16:8) — the same word that judges the guilty vindicates the righteous.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;But lately my people have risen up as an enemy — you strip the rich robe from those who pass by trustingly.&rdquo; Attacking the peaceable, stripping the garment of the trusting — covenant betrayal at its most intimate. At the crucifixion, the soldiers strip Christ's garments (John 19:23-24, fulfilling Ps 22:18) — the faithful and trusting one is stripped by those who should have been his people. The covenant violation that Micah describes reaches its nadir at the cross, where the covenant people hand over the covenant Lord to be stripped and crucified.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;The women of my people you drive out from their pleasant houses; from their young children you take away my splendor forever.&rdquo; The expulsion of the vulnerable — women and children driven from homes — violates the deepest covenantal obligations of neighbor-care. Christ's specific concern for the vulnerable (Matt 18:1-5; 19:13-15: &ldquo;let the little children come to me&rdquo;; Luke 18:3 the persistent widow) is the positive form of Micah's indictment. The splendor taken from the children is restored in the new creation: &ldquo;the kingdom of God belongs to such as these&rdquo; (Mark 10:14).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Arise and go, for this is no place to rest, because of uncleanness that destroys with a grievous destruction.&rdquo; Exile as the consequence of defiling the land — the land vomits out its inhabitants when they defile it (Lev 18:25). The pattern of exile and rest: Israel has no rest in the defiled land; Christ promises &ldquo;rest for your souls&rdquo; (Matt 11:29) in the new covenant. The true rest is not a geographic location but a person: &ldquo;there remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God&rdquo; (Heb 4:9) that the exile forfeited and Christ restores.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A theme: the false prophet who would prophesy wine and strong drink — &ldquo;if a man of wind and falsehood comes and preaches lies&rdquo; — exposes the market for comfortable prophecy: people prefer preachers who tell them what they want to hear (cf. 2 Tim 4:3-4: &ldquo;having itching ears they will accumulate for themselves teachers to suit their own passions&rdquo;). Christ's contrast is absolute: &ldquo;I am the truth&rdquo; (John 14:6) — not the comforting lie but the demanding and liberating truth. The test of a true prophet (his words come true) is the test the resurrection applies definitively to Christ.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I will surely assemble all of you, O Jacob; I will gather the remnant of Israel; I will set them together like sheep in a fold, like a flock in its pasture.&rdquo; The gathering Shepherd collecting the scattered remnant — this is the explicit type of the Good Shepherd. Christ quotes Ezek 34 (the same tradition) and applies it to himself: &ldquo;I have other sheep that are not of this fold; I must bring them also&rdquo; (John 10:16). The remnant-gathering promise of Mic 2:12 is fulfilled in Christ's mission: &ldquo;the Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost&rdquo; (Luke 19:10), gathering the scattered flock.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: &ldquo;He who opens the breach goes up before them; they break through and pass the gate, going out by it. Their king passes on before them, the LORD at their head.&rdquo; The <em>poretz</em> (breaker, the one who breaks through) leading the flock out through the breach — an image of the liberating king who goes ahead of his people, smashing the walls that confine them. This is one of the richest messianic types in Micah: Christ as the one who breaks through death (Acts 2:24: &ldquo;God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it&rdquo;) and leads the redeemed out from death's enclosure. John 10:3-4 applies the same shepherd-leader pattern to Christ: he &ldquo;goes before them, and the sheep follow him.&rdquo;</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Is it not for you to know justice?&rdquo; — the leaders of Israel are accountable for justice precisely because they were given authority to administer it. The God who holds them accountable is the God whose nature is justice (Ps 89:14: &ldquo;righteousness and justice are the foundation of your throne&rdquo;). Christ's woes against the scribes and Pharisees (Matt 23) are the NT form of Micah's challenge to the rulers: those entrusted with the law bear the heaviest accountability for its violation. The justice YHWH requires is the justice Christ both embodies and demands.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;You who hate the good and love evil, who tear the skin from my people.&rdquo; The inversion of the created moral order — hating good, loving evil — is the diagnostic of deep corruption. Paul uses the same categories: &ldquo;Although they know God's righteous decree that those who do such things deserve death, they not only continue to do these very things but also approve of those who practice them&rdquo; (Rom 1:32). Christ's coming as the &ldquo;good and true&rdquo; one (John 10:11, 14) into a world that hates the good explains the hostility he encounters: &ldquo;the light has come into the world, and people loved the darkness rather than the light&rdquo; (John 3:19).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: the cannibalistic image — rulers who &ldquo;eat the flesh of my people, break their bones in pieces, chop them up like meat for the pot&rdquo; — is the OT's most visceral description of exploitative leadership. Shepherds who devour the flock rather than protect it (Ezek 34 develops the same image at length). Christ as the Good Shepherd is the antithesis: he lays down his life for the sheep (John 10:11) instead of consuming them. The flesh that the corrupt shepherds devour from the people, Christ gives his own flesh for: &ldquo;my flesh is true food&rdquo; (John 6:55) — the eucharistic reversal of the cannibalistic exploitation Micah exposes.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Then they will cry out to the LORD, but he will not answer them; he will hide his face from them at that time.&rdquo; The hidden face of YHWH as divine judgment — withdrawal of the presence that had sustained them. The most devastating form of judgment is not external punishment but divine absence. Christ's cry from the cross — &ldquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rdquo; (Matt 27:46) — is the ultimate hidden face. The Son endures the hidden face not for his own evil deeds (unlike these rulers) but for ours, so that those who repent will never experience YHWH's permanent withdrawal: &ldquo;I will never leave you nor forsake you&rdquo; (Heb 13:5).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: the false prophets who &ldquo;cry peace when they have something to eat, but declare war against him who puts nothing into their mouths&rdquo; — their prophecies are market-driven, not Spirit-driven. The one true prophet who is not for sale is the contrast: Christ &ldquo;taught them as one who had authority, and not as their scribes&rdquo; (Matt 7:29). The false prophet speaks what the audience pays for; Christ speaks the truth regardless of cost (John 7:7: &ldquo;the world cannot hate you, but it hates me because I testify about it that its works are evil&rdquo;). The true prophet who speaks without payment becomes the one who is condemned by those who pay for comfortable prophecy.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: the judgment on false prophets — vision becomes darkness, divination becomes night, the sun goes down over them — is the reversal of prophetic light into blindness. The Day of the LORD as darkness for those who live by false light. Christ is the reversal: &ldquo;I am the light of the world; whoever follows me will not walk in darkness&rdquo; (John 8:12). The sun that sets on false prophets is the same sun that rises on those who fear YHWH's name: &ldquo;the sun of righteousness shall rise with healing in its wings&rdquo; (Mal 4:2). Christ is the light that the darkness of false prophecy cannot extinguish (John 1:5).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A theme: the seers covered their lips, the diviners disgraced — shame and silence when the word of God is withdrawn. The mouth covered was the gesture of ritual uncleanness (Lev 13:45: the leper covered his lip crying &ldquo;Unclean!&rdquo;). The false prophets' silence exposes them as the spiritual lepers they always were. The contrast is Christ, who never covers his lips, never loses the prophetic word, because he is himself the Word: the prophet greater than Moses who speaks with God face to face (Deut 18:15-18; John 1:1).</p>",
    "8": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;But as for me, I am filled with power, with the Spirit of the LORD, and with justice and might, to declare to Jacob his transgression and to Israel his sin.&rdquo; Micah's prophetic empowerment — the Spirit, justice, and might — contrasts directly with the false prophets' market-driven darkness (v6-7). The Spirit's empowerment for truthful witness is the OT pattern that reaches its fulfillment in Christ: &ldquo;the Spirit of the LORD is upon me, because he has anointed me to proclaim good news to the poor&rdquo; (Luke 4:18, citing Isa 61:1). The same Spirit that empowered Micah rests on Christ &ldquo;without measure&rdquo; (John 3:34).</p>",
    "9": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Hear this, you heads of the house of Jacob and rulers of the house of Israel, who detest justice and make crooked all that is straight.&rdquo; YHWH holds covenant leadership to the highest standard of justice; those who make straight things crooked are accountable to the one who is himself straight/upright (<em>yashar</em>). Christ &ldquo;makes straight&rdquo; all that is crooked — the one who fulfills the whole law and cannot be accused of making it crooked (John 8:46: &ldquo;which one of you convicts me of sin?&rdquo;). The very sin Micah condemns in Israel's rulers, Christ is entirely free of.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;who build Zion with blood and Jerusalem with iniquity.&rdquo; The city built on violent exploitation — a Zion constructed through injustice — cannot stand. The NT identifies a greater and permanent Zion: &ldquo;you have come to Mount Zion and to the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem&rdquo; (Heb 12:22). This city is not built with blood shed by its inhabitants' exploitation but with the blood of Christ who builds it (Matt 16:18: &ldquo;I will build my church&rdquo;). The corrupted earthly Zion is replaced by the indestructible heavenly city founded on the one righteous foundation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Its heads give judgment for a bribe; its priests teach for a price; its prophets practice divination for money.&rdquo; The complete commercialization of covenant service — every mediator between YHWH and the people operates for hire. The contrast is Christ, who gives his life without charge: &ldquo;You received without paying; give without pay&rdquo; (Matt 10:8); &ldquo;Come, everyone who thirsts, come to the waters; and he who has no money, come&rdquo; (Isa 55:1). The mediator who charges nothing for access to God is the answer to every corrupt mediator who charges everything.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Therefore because of you Zion shall be plowed as a field, and Jerusalem shall become a heap of ruins.&rdquo; The most shocking oracle in Micah — the holy city will be destroyed, plowed under like a common field. This was cited a century later (Jer 26:18-19) as the precedent for not killing Jeremiah. The destruction of Jerusalem in 586 BCE partially fulfilled it; the Roman destruction of 70 CE completed it (Luke 21:6: &ldquo;not one stone will be left here upon another that will not be thrown down&rdquo; — Christ's own prophecy echoing Micah). The plowing of the city is the judgment that the cross both absorbs and delays: Christ bears the covenant curse so the city has another generation to repent.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;In the latter days it shall come to pass that the mountain of the house of the LORD shall be established as the highest of the mountains.&rdquo; The vision of Zion as the cosmic center — the highest mountain, the place where all nations gather — is the OT eschatological hope for the universal reign of YHWH. The NT identifies the fulfillment: the mountain is Christ himself, and the gathering is his church drawn from all nations. Hebrews identifies the heavenly Jerusalem as the true fulfillment (Heb 12:22-24); Revelation 21 describes the new Jerusalem descending, with the nations streaming into it (Rev 21:24-26). What Micah sees in prophetic vision, Christ makes possible by his death and resurrection.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Many nations shall come and say, Come, let us go up to the mountain of the LORD... for out of Zion shall go forth the law, and the word of the LORD from Jerusalem.&rdquo; The nations voluntarily streaming to learn from YHWH — the reversal of Babel (Gen 11: scattered nations) in the eschatological gathering. The NT fulfillment is the Great Commission: &ldquo;make disciples of all nations... teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you&rdquo; (Matt 28:19-20). The &ldquo;law going out from Zion&rdquo; is the gospel going out from Jerusalem: &ldquo;you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth&rdquo; (Acts 1:8).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;They shall beat their swords into plowshares and their spears into pruning hooks; nation shall not lift up sword against nation; neither shall they learn war anymore.&rdquo; The eschatological peace — the conversion of instruments of destruction into instruments of cultivation — is the vision of the new creation. The NT identifies Christ as the one who establishes this peace: &ldquo;he himself is our peace&rdquo; (Eph 2:14); &ldquo;he has reconciled us to God through the cross, by which he put to death their hostility&rdquo; (Eph 2:16). The swords-into-plowshares vision is fulfilled first in the reconciliation between Jew and Gentile that Christ accomplishes (Eph 2:11-18), and finally in the new creation where there is no more war (Rev 21:4).</p>",
    "4": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;But they shall sit, every man under his vine and under his fig tree, and no one shall make them afraid.&rdquo; The vine and fig tree as the image of peace and security — rooted, at rest, unafraid. The OT's garden-imagery: Eden restored. The NT's form: &ldquo;Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest&rdquo; (Matt 11:28); &ldquo;I am the vine; you are the branches&rdquo; (John 15:5). To sit under one's own vine is to be in Christ, rooted in the one who is himself the vine from which the peaceful fruit grows. The &ldquo;no one shall make them afraid&rdquo; is the &ldquo;perfect love drives out fear&rdquo; of 1 John 4:18.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;For all the peoples walk each in the name of its god, but we will walk in the name of the LORD our God forever and ever.&rdquo; The covenant community's commitment to YHWH while the nations walk in false gods — and the eschatological confidence that this walk will continue &ldquo;forever and ever.&rdquo; The NT answer to the nations walking in their own gods is the universal mission: &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&rdquo; (Matt 28:18) — Christ's authority over every name, the name above every name (Phil 2:9-10), means that the &ldquo;name of the LORD&rdquo; in which the covenant community walks is fully revealed as the name of Jesus.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;In that day, declares the LORD, I will assemble the lame and gather those who have been driven away, and those whom I have afflicted.&rdquo; YHWH gathers the lame, the outcast, the afflicted — the exact population Jesus heals and welcomes (Matt 11:5: &ldquo;the lame walk... the poor have good news preached to them&rdquo;; Luke 14:21: &ldquo;bring in the poor and crippled and blind and lame&rdquo;). Christ's miracles of healing are not incidental displays of power but the enactment of the eschatological gathering that Micah announces — the kingdom arriving in the restoration of the broken.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;And the lame I will make the remnant, and those who were cast off a strong nation; and the LORD will reign over them in Mount Zion from this time forth and forevermore.&rdquo; The lame become the remnant; the outcast become the nation; YHWH reigns from Zion forever. The NT fulfillment is the church: &ldquo;God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong... so that no human being might boast in the presence of God&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:27-29). The eternal reign that begins in Zion is the reign of Christ that has no end: &ldquo;he will reign over the house of Jacob forever, and of his kingdom there will be no end&rdquo; (Luke 1:33).</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: &ldquo;And you, O tower of the flock (<em>Migdal-eder</em>), hill of the daughter of Zion, to you shall it come, the former dominion shall come, the kingdom of the daughter of Jerusalem.&rdquo; <em>Migdal-eder</em> (the tower of the flock) is the watchtower near Bethlehem where shepherds watched their flocks (Gen 35:21 places it near Bethlehem). Jewish tradition in the Targum Jonathan identifies this as the place where the King-Messiah would be revealed. The proximity to Micah 5:2 (the Bethlehem nativity prophecy) confirms the connection: the former dominion — the Davidic kingdom — comes to the very place where shepherds watched at night when the heavenly host announced the birth of the shepherd-king (Luke 2:8-14).</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Why do you cry aloud? Is there no king in you? Has your counselor perished, that pain seized you like a woman in labor?&rdquo; The absence of the king as the reason for the people's pain — when the king fails, the covenant community suffers like a woman in childbirth. The NT takes up the birth-pangs image for the new creation: &ldquo;the whole creation has been groaning together in the pains of childbirth until now&rdquo; (Rom 8:22); &ldquo;a woman giving birth to a child has pain&rdquo; (John 16:21). The labor that Micah describes — the people without their king — becomes in the NT the labor of the whole creation waiting for the King to be revealed: &ldquo;we wait eagerly for adoption as sons, the redemption of our bodies&rdquo; (Rom 8:23).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Be in anguish and groan, O daughter of Zion, like a woman in labor, for now you shall go out from the city and dwell in the open country; you shall go to Babylon. There you shall be rescued; there the LORD will redeem you from the hand of your enemies.&rdquo; The exile to Babylon as the birth-pangs before the redemption — suffering as the path to rescue. The NT develops this as the shape of redemptive suffering: &ldquo;through many tribulations we must enter the kingdom of God&rdquo; (Acts 14:22); and most explicitly in Heb 12:2: Christ &ldquo;for the joy set before him endured the cross&rdquo; — the suffering of the cross is the labor before the birth of the new creation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Now many nations are assembled against you, saying, Let her be defiled.&rdquo; The nations gathered against Jerusalem anticipates the ultimate gathering against Christ: &ldquo;the kings of the earth took their stand, and the rulers were gathered together against the Lord and against his Anointed&rdquo; (Acts 4:26-27, citing Ps 2:2), fulfilled at the passion of Christ. The defilement the nations sought for Jerusalem, Christ endures at the crucifixion — he is declared unclean, crucified outside the city gate (Heb 13:12). The nations' hostility reaches its fullest expression against the Lord's Anointed.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;But they do not know the thoughts of the LORD; they do not understand his plan, that he has gathered them as sheaves to the threshing floor.&rdquo; The nations who gather against Zion do not know that YHWH has gathered them for his own purposes — the threshing-floor judgment awaits. This reveals the sovereign God who uses even the hostility of enemies to accomplish his purposes. At the cross, the same irony operates: those who gathered against Christ do not know that his death is &ldquo;according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God&rdquo; (Acts 2:23) — their hostility becomes the instrument of the world's redemption.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Arise and thresh, O daughter of Zion, for I will make your horn iron and your hoofs bronze; you shall beat in pieces many peoples.&rdquo; The image of Zion as the threshing ox, consecrating the spoil to YHWH — the eschatological judgment carried out by the covenant community. The NT develops this into the church's participation in Christ's victory: &ldquo;the God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet&rdquo; (Rom 16:20); &ldquo;the saints will judge the world&rdquo; (1 Cor 6:2). The threshing that Micah assigns to Zion is accomplished first in Christ's victory over the powers (Col 2:15: &ldquo;he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame&rdquo;), and the church shares in that victory.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;With a rod they strike the ruler of Israel on the cheek.&rdquo; The humiliation of Israel's ruler — the judge struck on the cheek — is the OT image of ultimate degradation: to strike the cheek was the deepest insult to a person's honor. At the passion, the soldiers strike Jesus (Matt 26:67: they &ldquo;slapped him&rdquo;; John 18:22: an officer &ldquo;struck Jesus with his hand&rdquo;) — the ultimate degradation of the ultimate King. The ruler of Israel who is struck on the cheek becomes, in Micah's next verse, the eternal ruler from Bethlehem: the one humiliated is the one whose origin is from eternity.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Therefore he will give them up until the time when she who is in labor has given birth; then the rest of his brothers shall return to the people of Israel.&rdquo; The labor and birth of v3 connects with v2: the one born in Bethlehem is the answer to the &ldquo;giving up&rdquo; — the period of abandonment ends with his birth. The NT takes up this pattern: the interval between the promise and the fulfillment is the labor pain before the birth. Paul in Gal 4:4: &ldquo;when the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son, born of woman&rdquo; — the labor ends; the child is born; the scattering ends and the brothers return. The birth in Bethlehem is the event that ends the &ldquo;giving up.&rdquo;</p>",
    "4": "<p>A type: &ldquo;And he shall stand and shepherd his flock in the strength of the LORD, in the majesty of the name of the LORD his God. And they shall dwell secure, for now he shall be great to the ends of the earth.&rdquo; The Shepherd-King who stands to feed his flock in YHWH's strength — this is the direct type of Christ as the Good Shepherd: &ldquo;I am the good shepherd; I know my own and my own know me&rdquo; (John 10:14); &ldquo;he will be great to the ends of the earth&rdquo; is the Micah form of &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&rdquo; (Matt 28:18). The shepherd standing in YHWH's strength anticipates the resurrection: the standing shepherd is the risen shepherd who &ldquo;stands at the right hand of God&rdquo; (Acts 7:56).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;And he shall be their peace.&rdquo; <em>Veha-yah zeh shalom</em> — the five-word declaration of the Messiah's identity as peace itself. Paul quotes the same thought in Eph 2:14: &ldquo;he himself is our peace&rdquo; — the same construction, the same declaration. The Messiah does not merely bring peace as a gift; he is peace as his identity. Christ reconciles Jew and Gentile, humanity and God, in his own person — the horizontal and vertical dimensions of the shalom that Micah announces. Micah's five words become Paul's theological thesis in Ephesians 2: the peace is not a geopolitical achievement but a person, and that person is Jesus.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;They shall shepherd the land of Assyria with the sword.&rdquo; The reversal of the Assyrian threat — the Messiah's shepherds will rule in Assyria, the land of the oppressor. The NT's form is the Roman-era reversal: those who were persecuted by Rome eventually witnessed to Rome, and Rome became the vehicle of the gospel's spread to the ends of the earth. The empire that threatened becomes the territory of the kingdom. Christ's commission pushes into every hostile territory: &ldquo;I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it&rdquo; (Matt 16:18).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;The remnant of Jacob shall be in the midst of many peoples like dew from the LORD, like showers on the grass, which do not wait for a man or linger for human help.&rdquo; The remnant as life-giving dew among the nations — independent of human agency, purely divine in origin. The NT church is the form of this remnant: &ldquo;not by might, nor by power, but by my Spirit, says the LORD of hosts&rdquo; (Zech 4:6); the gospel spreads not through political power but through the Spirit's work that does not &ldquo;wait for man.&rdquo; Christ sends the Spirit who blows &ldquo;where he wills&rdquo; (John 3:8) — the dew that falls without human direction.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;The remnant of Jacob shall be among the nations, in the midst of many peoples, like a lion among the beasts of the forest.&rdquo; The double image — dew (v7) and lion (v8) — shows the two faces of the messianic community: life-giving gentleness and judging power. Christ is described with both images in Revelation: &ldquo;the Lion of the tribe of Judah&rdquo; who is also &ldquo;a Lamb standing, as though it had been slain&rdquo; (Rev 5:5-6). The remnant that is both dew and lion participates in the character of its King, who is both the shepherd who tends gently and the judge who acts with final authority.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;Your hand shall be lifted up over your adversaries, and all your enemies shall be cut off.&rdquo; The raised hand of victory over adversaries is the covenant warfare language. At the resurrection, Christ's hand is lifted up over every adversary: &ldquo;he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:25); &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&rdquo; (Matt 28:18). The adversaries cut off are not nations but the powers behind the nations: &ldquo;he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame&rdquo; (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;In that day, declares the LORD, I will cut off your horses from among you and will destroy your chariots.&rdquo; The removal of the instruments of military power — horses and chariots, Israel's temptation to trust in military might rather than YHWH (cf. Ps 20:7: &ldquo;some trust in chariots and some in horses, but we trust in the name of the LORD our God&rdquo;). The kingdom that Christ establishes does not advance by military force: &ldquo;my kingdom is not of this world; if my kingdom were of this world, my servants would have been fighting&rdquo; (John 18:36). The Messiah who comes on a donkey (Zech 9:9, fulfilled in Matt 21:5) deliberately refuses the war-horse.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;I will cut off the cities of your land and throw down all your strongholds.&rdquo; The removal of human-built defenses — the cities and fortresses in which Israel trusted instead of YHWH. The NT equivalent is the demolition of spiritual strongholds: &ldquo;the weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh but have divine power to destroy strongholds&rdquo; (2 Cor 10:4). Christ does not merely remove external enemies but the internal strongholds of self-reliance — &ldquo;the wisdom of this world&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:20) and &ldquo;the flesh&rdquo; (Gal 5:16-17) — which are the deeper fortifications against the kingdom.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;I will cut off sorceries from your hand, and you shall have no more tellers of fortunes.&rdquo; The elimination of false mediators — sorceries and fortune-tellers who claimed access to divine knowledge outside of YHWH's revealed word. The NT fulfillment: at Ephesus, those who practiced magic &ldquo;brought their books together and burned them&rdquo; in response to the gospel (Acts 19:19). Christ as the true mediator (1 Tim 2:5: &ldquo;there is one mediator between God and men&rdquo;) makes all false mediation obsolete: the one who is himself the truth (John 14:6) renders fortune-telling not just forbidden but unnecessary.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;I will cut off your carved images and your pillars, and you shall bow down no more to the work of your hands.&rdquo; The elimination of idolatry — all the &ldquo;works of your hands&rdquo; that Israel bowed down to. The NT identifies the deepest idolatry as covetousness (&ldquo;which is idolatry,&rdquo; Col 3:5) and the worship of the self (Rom 1:25: worshipping &ldquo;the creature rather than the Creator&rdquo;). Christ's first commandment (&ldquo;you shall love the Lord your God with all your heart&rdquo;, Matt 22:37) is the positive form of Micah's cutting off: not merely removing false worship but replacing it with the one true object of worship.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;I will uproot your Asherah poles from among you and destroy your cities.&rdquo; The Asherah poles — the fertility cult symbols that Israel repeatedly adopted from Canaanite neighbors — represent the persistent human tendency to combine YHWH-worship with surrounding religious cultures. The NT equivalent is Paul's warning against syncretism: &ldquo;What agreement has the temple of God with idols?&rdquo; (2 Cor 6:16); &ldquo;you cannot drink the cup of the Lord and the cup of demons&rdquo; (1 Cor 10:21). Christ's exclusive claim (&ldquo;I am the way, and the truth, and the life; no one comes to the Father except through me&rdquo;, John 14:6) is the answer to every Asherah.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;And in anger and wrath I will execute vengeance on the nations that did not obey.&rdquo; The divine wrath that pursues disobedience — not arbitrary violence but the moral coherence of the universe in which covenant violation has consequences. The NT does not eliminate this: &ldquo;the wrath of God is revealed from heaven against all ungodliness and unrighteousness of men&rdquo; (Rom 1:18); &ldquo;do not be deceived: God is not mocked&rdquo; (Gal 6:7). But the NT adds the good news: &ldquo;God did not destine us for wrath but to obtain salvation through our Lord Jesus Christ&rdquo; (1 Thess 5:9). The wrath that Micah announces falls on Christ (Rom 3:25-26) so that it need not fall on those who trust him.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Hear what the LORD says: Arise, plead your case before the mountains.&rdquo; The covenant lawsuit (<em>rib</em>) — YHWH calling Israel to legal trial before the eternal witnesses of the mountains. The God who enters legal proceedings with his own people reveals a God who submits to rational accountability, not arbitrary power: &ldquo;Come now, let us reason together&rdquo; (Isa 1:18). Christ invites the same rationality: &ldquo;Which one of you convicts me of sin?&rdquo; (John 8:46); &ldquo;If what I said is wrong, bear witness about the wrong; but if what I said is right, why do you strike me?&rdquo; (John 18:23). The God who reasons with his people in Micah is the God who reasons with his accusers in the Gospels.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Hear, O mountains, the LORD's indictment... for the LORD has an indictment against his people, and he will contend with Israel.&rdquo; The everlasting foundations of the earth are called as witnesses to YHWH's case against Israel — the most ancient and permanent aspects of creation testify to covenant violation. The NT's form: &ldquo;the heavens and earth he has kept until the day of judgment and destruction of the ungodly&rdquo; (2 Pet 3:7). Creation witnesses against human sin; only Christ's righteousness credited to those who believe silences the indictment.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;O my people, what have I done to you? In what have I wearied you? Testify against me.&rdquo; The most plaintive verse in Micah — YHWH's direct appeal to his people: if you are leaving me, tell me what I have done wrong. This is the language of covenant love grieved by rejection. The NT's fulfillment: Christ's final question to Peter (&ldquo;Simon, son of John, do you love me?&rdquo;, John 21:17) and his lament over Jerusalem (&ldquo;How often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings, and you were not willing!&rdquo;, Matt 23:37) are the incarnate forms of YHWH's plea in Micah. The God who pleads in Mic 6:3 suffers in Matt 27.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;For I brought you up from the land of Egypt and redeemed you from the house of slavery; and I sent before you Moses, Aaron, and Miriam.&rdquo; YHWH's recitation of his salvific acts — the Exodus as the ground of the covenant relationship. The God who recounts what he has done for Israel is the God who in Christ says &ldquo;it is finished&rdquo; (John 19:30) — the complete salvific act accomplished. The Exodus recital is the OT pattern; the passion narrative is the NT fulfillment of the same pattern: redemption from slavery, leadership through the wilderness, entrance into rest (Heb 3-4). Christ is the new Moses, Aaron (the High Priest, Heb 4:14-5:10), and the way (John 14:6).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Remember what Balak king of Moab devised, and what Balaam the son of Beor answered him... that you may know the saving acts of the LORD.&rdquo; The Balaam episode — where a hired enemy-prophet was compelled to bless instead of curse — is cited as evidence of YHWH's saving faithfulness. The saving acts of YHWH that Micah recalls are the basis for trust. The NT's fullest &ldquo;saving act&rdquo; recitation is in Paul's preaching (Acts 13:17-41: a Micah-style rehearsal of salvific history that culminates in the resurrection). The God who turned Balaam's curse into blessing turns the curse of the cross into the blessing of justification (Gal 3:13-14).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;With what shall I come before the LORD and bow myself before God on high? Shall I come before him with burnt offerings, with calves a year old?&rdquo; The question of acceptable worship — what does YHWH actually require? The escalating series of potential offerings (burnt offerings, calves, rams, rivers of oil, firstborn children) builds to the reductio ad absurdum: no sacrifice, however costly, answers the question. The NT's answer: &ldquo;since we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus&rdquo; (Heb 10:19) — the one sacrifice that actually suffices is not a human offering but the self-offering of Christ. The question Micah's worshipper asks, Christ alone answers.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Will the LORD be pleased with thousands of rams, with ten thousands of rivers of oil? Shall I give my firstborn for my transgression, the fruit of my body for the sin of my soul?&rdquo; The impossible arithmetic of sacrifice: even infinite rams, infinite oil, even the child's life — none of it reaches the debt. But the question about the firstborn for transgression has a precise answer in the NT: &ldquo;God did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all&rdquo; (Rom 8:32). The firstborn that Micah's worshipper considers giving is given — but God gives his own firstborn Son (Col 1:15: &ldquo;the firstborn over all creation&rdquo;). The unanswerable question finds its answer in the cross.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;He has told you, O man, what is good; and what does the LORD require of you but to do justice, and to love kindness (<em>chesed</em>), and to walk humbly with your God?&rdquo; The ethical summary of the OT that Jesus himself invokes — Jesus in Matt 23:23 calls &ldquo;justice and mercy and faithfulness&rdquo; the &ldquo;weightier matters of the law&rdquo; that the Pharisees neglect. Christ is the living fulfillment of Mic 6:8: he does perfect justice (Acts 3:14: &ldquo;the Holy and Righteous One&rdquo;), loves perfect <em>chesed</em> (John 13:1: &ldquo;having loved his own who were in the world, he loved them to the end&rdquo;), and walks in perfect humility (Phil 2:8: &ldquo;humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death&rdquo;). What YHWH requires, Christ embodies; what Christ embodies, he works in those who trust him.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;The voice of the LORD cries to the city: wisdom shall fear your name.&rdquo; YHWH speaks to the city; wisdom is defined by fearing his name. The God who speaks is the God whose word is wisdom. The NT identifies Christ as the wisdom of God: &ldquo;Christ, in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&rdquo; (Col 2:3); &ldquo;Christ the power of God and the wisdom of God&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:24). To fear the name of YHWH is, in the NT, to fear and reverence the name of Jesus, in whom YHWH's name is fully revealed (John 17:6: &ldquo;I have manifested your name to the people whom you gave me&rdquo;).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Can I forget any longer the treasures of wickedness in the house of the wicked, and the scant measure that is accursed?&rdquo; YHWH's omniscient awareness of the hidden dishonest scales — &ldquo;can I forget?&rdquo; The God who never forgets the weights and measures of injustice is the God before whom &ldquo;no creature is hidden, and all are naked and exposed&rdquo; (Heb 4:13). Christ's final judgment includes everything hidden: &ldquo;God will bring every deed into judgment, with every secret thing, whether good or evil&rdquo; (Eccl 12:14; cf. Matt 12:36: &ldquo;for every careless word... you will give account&rdquo;). The scales Micah's merchants manipulate, Christ weighs with perfect precision.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A revelation of God: &ldquo;Shall I acquit the man with wicked scales and with a bag of deceitful weights?&rdquo; — the rhetorical answer is no. YHWH will not acquit the guilty. This is the problem of justice that the gospel addresses: how can YHWH both &ldquo;not acquit the guilty&rdquo; (Exod 34:7) and yet justify sinners (Rom 4:5)? The answer is the cross: &ldquo;God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement... he did it to demonstrate his righteousness at the present time, so as to be just and the one who justifies those who have faith in Jesus&rdquo; (Rom 3:25-26). YHWH does not acquit — he condemns, but in Christ, the condemnation falls on the one who bore it for us.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;Your wealthy men are full of violence; your inhabitants speak lies, and their tongue is deceitful in their mouth.&rdquo; Wealth, violence, and deception as a unified syndrome of covenant breakdown. James 5:1-6 echoes this exactly against those who have withheld wages; Rev 18:11-13 catalogues the merchants of Babylon whose wealth is built on exploitation. Christ's &ldquo;blessed are the poor in spirit&rdquo; (Matt 5:3) and &ldquo;woe to you who are rich&rdquo; (Luke 6:24) are the NT forms of Micah's indictment of wealthy violence.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Therefore I strike you with a grievous blow, making you desolate because of your sins.&rdquo; The divine blow of covenant judgment. The NT uses the same image for Christ: &ldquo;it was the will of the LORD to crush him; he has put him to grief&rdquo; (Isa 53:10). The grievous blow that falls on Micah's sinful community falls, in the NT, on the one who bore the sins of the community — so that the blow that is deserved by many falls on the one who deserves it not at all. The desolation Micah threatens is what Christ endures on the cross (&ldquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rdquo;, Matt 27:46) in order to prevent the permanent desolation of those who trust him.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;You shall eat, but not be satisfied, and there shall be hunger within you.&rdquo; The curse of hunger despite eating — the covenant curse that reverses the blessing of satisfied feasting (Deut 28:47: &ldquo;because you did not serve the LORD your God with joyfulness and gladness of heart&rdquo;). Christ is the reversal of this curse: &ldquo;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst&rdquo; (John 6:35). The hunger that the covenant curse installs, Christ removes — not by providing food but by being himself the food that permanently satisfies.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A theme: &ldquo;You shall sow but not reap; you shall tread olives but not anoint yourselves with oil.&rdquo; The covenant curse of futile labor — work that produces nothing usable. The reversal of the creation mandate in which labor yields fruit. The NT's form: &ldquo;apart from me you can do nothing&rdquo; (John 15:5) — without connection to the vine, all labor is futile. Connected to Christ, labor becomes fruitful: &ldquo;I am the vine; you are the branches. Whoever abides in me and I in him, he it is that bears much fruit&rdquo; (John 15:5). The fruitlessness of the covenant curse is reversed in the fruitfulness of the new covenant vine.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;For you have kept the statutes of Omri, and all the works of the house of Ahab; and you have walked in their counsels, that I may make you a desolation, and your inhabitants a hissing.&rdquo; Omri and Ahab — the two kings most associated with syncretism, Baal worship, and social injustice in the northern kingdom — become the pattern that Judah has imitated. Following the worst precedents always leads to the worst outcomes. The NT equivalent is Paul's catalog of bad examples in 1 Cor 10:1-11: &ldquo;these things took place as examples for us, that we might not desire evil as they did.&rdquo; Christ is the positive example that replaces every negative one: &ldquo;I have given you an example, that you also should do just as I have done to you&rdquo; (John 13:15).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'micah')
    merge_comm(existing, MICAH)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'micah', existing)
    print('Micah 1-6 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
